In the initial state, each agent knows only their own secret. For all agents to become experts (know all secrets), they must exchange information through calls. Each call connects two agents, allowing them to share all the information they have. 

To show that at least $n-1$ calls are needed, consider that each call can be represented as an edge in a graph, where each node represents an agent. The calls form a graph where each edge connects two nodes that have exchanged information. For all agents to know all secrets, the graph must be connected. A connected graph with $n$ nodes must have at least $n-1$ edges. Therefore, at least $n-1$ calls are needed.

